'vtable':{
  badge:'Stage 9 · Virtual Dispatch',bc:'var(--ra)',
  title:'vtable (Virtual Method Table)',
  def:'Every class has a vtable — a table of method pointers for its virtual (non-private, non-static, non-final) methods. When invokevirtual is executed, the JVM reads the vtable index from the bytecode (fixed at compile time) and jumps to the method pointer at that index. O(1) dispatch.',
  points:[
    'vtable stored in the class\'s Klass structure (in Metaspace, part of the class metadata)',
    'Inheritance: subclass vtable starts with all parent\'s vtable entries (in same positions). Overriding a method = updating that slot to point to the new implementation',
    'vtable index: determined at compile time by javac. Fixed for a given method signature across all subclasses',
    'invokevirtual bytecode: reads object\'s Klass pointer → reads vtable → reads slot N → calls method pointer',
    'JIT devirtualization: if JIT knows (via class hierarchy analysis CHA) there\'s only ONE implementation of a virtual method, it can inline the call directly, eliminating the vtable lookup entirely',
    'Performance: vtable dispatch is very fast (~2-5ns). The bottleneck is usually branch misprediction when different types are seen interleaved'
  ],
  tip:'Why final methods are faster: final methods cannot be overridden, so JIT can always devirtualize and inline them without CHA. That\'s why StringBuilder.append() is final and much faster than if it were virtual. More importantly, method inlining enables further optimizations (escape analysis, loop optimizations) across the call boundary.'
},
'itable':{
  badge:'Stage 9 · Virtual Dispatch',bc:'var(--ra)',
  title:'itable (Interface Method Table)',
  def:'Used for invokeinterface. Unlike vtable where the method index is fixed at compile time, interface methods can appear at different positions in different implementing classes\' vtables. The itable maps an interface\'s methods to the correct position in the implementing class\'s vtable.',
  points:[
    'Problem: if class A implements Comparable and Serializable, and class B implements only Comparable, the same compareTo() method is at DIFFERENT vtable offsets in A vs B',
    'Solution: itable. Each class has an itable mapping (interface, method_index) pairs to its concrete vtable slots',
    'invokeinterface is SLOWER than invokevirtual: must search the itable (linear scan in classic implementation; JIT uses inline caches to short-circuit this)',
    'JIT optimization: after seeing the same concrete type at an interface call site, JIT inserts a type check + direct vtable call (monomorphic inline cache). No itable lookup',
    'Java 8 default interface methods: stored in interface\'s own itable. Implementing classes inherit them unless overridden',
    'Modern JVMs: JIT effectively eliminates itable overhead for monomorphic/bimorphic call sites through inline caching'
  ],
  tip:'Interface vs abstract class performance: historically invokeinterface was slower. With modern JIT and inline caches, the difference is negligible for monomorphic/bimorphic call sites. Only megamorphic (4+ concrete types) call sites through interfaces have measurable overhead — and even then, it\'s usually not the bottleneck.'
},
'inline-caches':{
  badge:'Stage 9 · Virtual Dispatch',bc:'var(--ra)',
  title:'Inline Caches (Mono / Poly / Megamorphic)',
  def:'JIT optimization for virtual dispatch. Instead of going through the vtable every time, the JIT remembers which concrete type (or types) it has seen at a call site and generates a fast-path type check + direct call. Three states with very different performance characteristics.',
  points:[
    'Monomorphic (1 concrete type): JIT generates: if (type == CachedType) { call cachedMethod directly } else { deopt / fallback vtable }. Direct call = no vtable lookup + CPU branch predictor can learn it = extremely fast. Method can be inlined',
    'Bimorphic (2 types): JIT generates two type checks + two direct calls. Still fast, still potentially inlinable',
    'Polymorphic (3-4 types): JIT generates a type switch. Fast but cannot inline. Some JVMs handle up to 8 types',
    'Megamorphic (5+ types): JIT gives up on inline cache. Falls back to vtable/itable lookup every time. No inlining. Can be 5-10x slower than monomorphic. Profile-guided: JIT won\'t even JIT-compile the call as direct if it\'s seen too many types',
    'Practical impact: if a hot method called through an interface receives 10+ different concrete types, it becomes megamorphic. Restructure to limit the number of types at each call site',
    'JVM flag: -XX:+PrintInlining shows inlining decisions and why inlining was refused (often "megamorphic")'
  ],
  tip:'Megamorphic call site FAANG example: a parser that calls process(Event e) where Event has 20 subclasses. If all 20 types flow through the same call site, it\'s megamorphic. Solution: dispatch before the hot loop (visitor pattern, or switch-on-type before the loop), so the inner call site sees only 1-2 types.'
},
'invokedynamic':{
  badge:'Stage 9 · Lambda Internals',bc:'var(--ra)',
  title:'invokedynamic (indy) — Java 7+',
  def:'A bytecode instruction that defers method dispatch to user-defined "bootstrap" code at runtime. On first invocation, the bootstrap method resolves the call site to a MethodHandle (or call site object). Subsequent invocations use the cached linkage — extremely fast. Used for lambdas, string concatenation (+), dynamic languages (Groovy, JRuby).',
  points:[
    'First call: JVM invokes the bootstrap method specified in the bytecode. Bootstrap runs once and returns a CallSite (constant, mutable, or volatile)',
    'ConstantCallSite: call site is permanently linked after first bootstrap. Used for lambdas — same lambda always calls same bootstrap. JIT can inline completely',
    'MutableCallSite: call site can be re-linked (for dynamic languages that might redefine methods)',
    'String concatenation: Java 9+ compiles "Hello " + name + "!" to invokedynamic + StringConcatFactory bootstrap. More flexible than StringBuilder; JVM can choose best strategy',
    'Advantage over reflection: MethodHandle dispatch is JIT-inlineable. Reflection is not (crosses JVM boundary). invokedynamic + MethodHandle = same performance as direct method call after JIT warmup',
    'Bootstrap method resolution: occurs in constant pool. Bootstrap method itself is a static method in a bootstrap class (e.g., LambdaMetafactory, StringConcatFactory)'
  ],
  tip:'Why is invokedynamic used for lambdas instead of anonymous inner classes? Anonymous inner classes create a new .class file per lambda (compiled to disk). invokedynamic + LambdaMetafactory generates the implementation class at RUNTIME using ASM bytecode generation. Only one .class file needed, the functional interface. Faster startup, lower memory footprint.'
},
'method-handle':{
  badge:'Stage 9 · Lambda Internals',bc:'var(--ra)',
  title:'MethodHandle (java.lang.invoke)',
