'virtual-threads':{
  badge:'Stage 11 · Project Loom',bc:'#4cc9f0',
  title:'Virtual Threads (Java 21 — Project Loom)',
  def:'Virtual threads are lightweight threads managed by the JVM scheduler, not the OS. Millions can exist simultaneously. When a virtual thread blocks (I/O, sleep, lock), the JVM parks it and mounts another virtual thread on the same carrier (OS) thread. No OS thread stack wasted on blocking.',
  points:[
    'Creation: Thread.ofVirtual().start(runnable) or Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()',
    'Carrier threads: a ForkJoinPool of OS threads (default: number of CPUs). Virtual threads are scheduled onto carriers',
    'Blocking I/O: when a virtual thread calls a blocking operation (Socket.read, Files.readAllBytes), JVM intercepts via continuation mechanism → unmounts virtual thread from carrier → carrier is free to run other virtual threads → when I/O completes, virtual thread is remounted and continues',
    'Continuation: the call stack of a virtual thread is stored as a heap object (Continuation) when unmounted. This is why virtual threads can be so lightweight (no OS stack allocated while parked)',
    'Pinning: virtual thread is PINNED to carrier (cannot unmount) when: inside synchronized block, calling native JNI method. Pinning defeats the purpose — use ReentrantLock instead of synchronized in virtual thread code',
    'Structured concurrency (Java 21 preview): StructuredTaskScope groups virtual thread tasks — all fail together, results collected together. Like try-with-resources for concurrent tasks',
    'Thread-local variables: VTs inherit from parent VT. Use ScopedValues (Java 21) instead of ThreadLocal for better VT compatibility'
  ],
  code:'// Thread-per-request with virtual threads:\ntry (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {\n  for (var request : requests) {\n    executor.submit(() -> handleRequest(request));\n  }\n}  // waits for all\n// 10,000 concurrent requests → 10,000 virtual threads\n// Only ~N_CPU carrier threads actually running at once',
  tip:'Virtual threads do NOT make CPU-bound work faster. They solve the C10K problem: with OS threads, 10,000 concurrent I/O-blocking threads = 10,000 OS thread stacks (≈80GB RAM). With virtual threads, 10,000 concurrent I/O tasks = ~CPU_COUNT OS threads + 10,000 heap objects (~few KB each). Eliminates the need for reactive/async code (CompletableFuture chains) for I/O concurrency.'
