'tlab':{
  badge:'Stage 13 · Allocation',bc:'#f472b6',
  title:'Thread Local Allocation Buffer (TLAB)',
  def:'The JVM\'s mechanism for extremely fast object allocation. To avoid threads fighting over a global lock on the heap\'s Eden space, each thread is given its own small chunk of Eden memory called a TLAB.',
  points:[
    'Bump-the-pointer: Allocating an object in a TLAB simply means moving a pointer forward by the object\'s size. Takes only a few CPU instructions.',
    'No Locks: Because the buffer is exclusive to the thread, allocation requires zero synchronization or Compare-And-Swap (CAS) operations.',
    'Exhaustion: When a TLAB fills up, the thread requests a new one from Eden. This request is the "slow path" and requires synchronization (usually a CAS on the global Eden pointer).',
    'Large Objects: Objects too large for a TLAB (or sometimes even Eden) are allocated directly in the Old Generation (Humongous objects in G1 GC).',
